Obviously not. The monster just let out a roar and tried to charge directly at Sasilin. Thank goodness, Sasilin, although large in size, was still agile enough to dodge in time. However, Nisi couldn't help but scream, almost slipping off Sasilin's smooth scales.
"How can we kill them?" Nisi shouted.
"Aim for their heads!"
"It's too difficult!"
Sasilin roared, circled around, and flew toward the mountain he called home. The black monster followed closely, but when it was attacked by fire from behind, it seemed somewhat panicked. This monster had not yet realized it now had another opponent. Sasilin slowed down and then struck the monster's head with his tail, sending it off course, and the monster became even more panicked.
The monster roared, his throat making a hissing sound, flying straight upward while continuously spitting something into the air. Suddenly, the surroundings turned pitch black, as if the monster was absorbing the light from the sky and replacing it with eternal darkness.
Sasilin suddenly went blind, trying to step back but found himself colliding with the branches, then falling to the ground. The monster seemed to know exactly where Sasilin had fallen, flying straight toward him and bringing that dark cloud with it.
"Kayer!" Tenuk shouted, flying out of the cloud and beginning to spiral, trying to locate Nisi and Sasilin in the darkness below. "What should we do? Kayer…? Kayer, where are you?"
Nisi struggled to stand up. She felt certain she had broken her bones, but her strange, unnatural healing ability had already begun to take effect. Sasilin's situation was different; he lay helpless on the ground, leaning against a tree he had knocked over. Nisi tried to make her way toward Sasilin, but everything was pitch black in front of her, and she could almost see nothing. There were terrifying shadows everywhere, and something was shrieking within them.
A terrible, club-like tail smashed down onto the ground, knocking Nisi over. She noticed the tail was swinging wildly, but its target seemed not to be her. Nisi barely managed to see that the monster was roaring, clawing frantically at the shadows it had created. Something was moving through the darkness, waiting for the right moment to strike the monster.
Suddenly, a gunshot shattered the air, and the monster fell silent, lying motionless on the ground. The surrounding darkness dispersed, revealing the truth of the situation. Kayer stood on the monster's corpse, holding a rifle, breathing heavily.
"That was... one of the strangest shadow leaps I've ever done... Tantok Cateron..." Kayer panted. Somehow, his eyes glowed with black light, and a surge of dark energy flowed within him. But just as Kayer spoke, his organic armor regained its color, and his eyes returned to their normal yellow.
After a while, Nisi finally understood what had happened. They all knew that Kayer possessed eerie shadow abilities, but he rarely used them, as most people considered them extremely evil and frightening. However, Nisi didn't know that Kayer could use these abilities in any darkness. Moreover, from Kayer's reaction, it seemed that he was also surprised himself.
"Are you okay?" Nisi couldn't help asking.
"I'm fine. I killed that thing, and I'll be fine soon." Kayer looked at his "masterpiece," and at that moment, Tenuk landed beside him, reverting back to his original Spartus form.
Now, the monster was no longer moving, and they could finally get a good look at what it really was. Its skin was black and shiny, covered with a sticky liquid that clung tightly to its body. It had four wings and four legs, each leg ending in long, sharp claws, and two straight horns growing from its skull.
Tunuk and Kayer hadn't even had time to ask what kind of thing this was, when another monster suddenly leaped out from the nearby bushes, screaming. At that moment, a familiar car crashed into the monster's side, and the monster slid for a distance before coming to a stop by Nisi's feet. Nisi didn't hesitate; she grabbed the shotgun and fired a shot at the monster's head, killing it instantly.
"Ow..." Retwick muttered as he sat in the driver's seat, then awkwardly turned off the engine and climbed out of the truck. "Er, I didn't mean to do that. Are you all okay?"
"You missed all the fun!" Tunuk said with a sigh. "Where were you?"
"You left me behind," Retwick sighed. "I tried my best to catch up..." "Please, what are these terrible things?"
Retwick's question was answered by Sasilin, who had already stood up. He was covered in wounds and scratches, looking a bit dazed, but his injuries seemed not to be serious.
"You killed the corrupted one! Those infected monsters. When the corruption attacked your god, these creatures were left here."
"You mean… we… helped kill the terrible monster god?" Tunuk stammered a bit.
"Yes, that's exactly what happened. There may be more corrupted ones. But I can't shoot them in the head. I don't have a gun. And fighting them one-on-one isn't fair, right?" Sasilin walked up to Kayer and patted his head. "Thank you, little guy. You made me think of my old friend Arcadin. Only you aren't as ruthless, and you don't have his destructive power that can destroy the universe."
"Uh… thank you… I think… " Kayer shrugged. "So, uh, did we complete the mission?"
Nisi shrugged her shoulders, picked up the camera, and took a few photos of the monsters that were definitely dead. Then, she pulled out her favorite knife—the elegant Death Knife—and began cutting off one of the monster's horns, then the other. However, right at the moment Nisi finished the cutting, the monsters suddenly started self-combusting, turning into a pile of ashes in a short time. The horns she had cut off also turned to ash.
"Well... this is a double-edged sword..." Nisi sighed. "At least I still have the photos, right?"
